description: growing with Cephaloziella divaricata var. scabra. you can really see the difference between the 2 even though the species are the same.

Growing in mountain ponds.  Distinct inflated cells-  "cellular projections on the dorsal surface, margins often serrate".  Whittemore rejected the "C. divaricata var. asperifolia" which is becoming the more prevelent name around the world but his key was specifically for California so im going ot stick with his "scabra".  I tried putting in the best photos of this "inflated cells" and teeth.   Some of these photos were from 2006 when they were fresh and i tried to get fresh new photos but the specimens were so full of algae it was difficult to get anything.  Growing with regular Cephaloziella divaricata.   2 of the photos show dried specimens with fresh water clams.  these are only about 1-2 mm long.  Location is obscured do to extreme rare species in this meadow.

There were four of these outside of our house. They were not close to each other – are spiders more solitary than most other bugs?
